// Problem: SACKNAP
//Is this Knapsack -- partially accepted(25 Points)
import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;
class Solution {
	static Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
	public static void reverse(int[] arr, int l, int r) {
		int d = (r - l + 1) / 2;
		for (int i = 0; i < d; i++) {
			int t = arr[l + i];
			arr[l + i] = arr[r - i];
			arr[r - i] = t;
		}
	}
	// QUICK MATHS
    private static int gcd(int a, int b) {
        if (b == 0)
            return a;
        return gcd(b, a % b);
    }

    private static long gcd(long a, long b) {
        if (b == 0)
            return a;
        return gcd(b, a % b);
    }

    private static int lcm(int a, int b) {
        return (a / gcd(a, b)) * b;
    }

    private static long lcm(long a, long b) {
        return (a / gcd(a, b)) * b;
    }
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		solve();
	}
	// BIT MAGIC
    public int getMSB(int b) {
        return (int)(Math.log(b) / Math.log(2));
    }
    //HELPER FUNCTIONS
    private static int[] nextArray(int n){
        int arr[]=new int[n];
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            arr[i]=sc.nextInt();
        }
        return arr;
    }
    private static long[] nextLongArray(int n){
        long arr[]=new long[n];
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            arr[i]=sc.nextLong();
        }
        return arr;
    }
    static int[] copy(int A[]) {
        int B[]=new int[A.length];
        for(int i=0;i<A.length;i++) {
            B[i]=A[i];
        }
        return B;
    }
    static long[] copy(long A[]) {
        long B[]=new long[A.length];
        for(int i=0;i<A.length;i++) {
            B[i]=A[i];
        }
        return B;
    }
    static long sum(int A[]) {
    	long sum=0;
    	for(int i : A) {
    		sum+=i;
    	}
    	return sum;
    }
    static long sum(long A[]) {
    	long sum=0;
    	for(long i : A) {
    		sum+=i;
    	}
    	return sum;
    }
    static void print(int A[]) {
    	for(int i : A) {
    		System.out.print(i+" ");
    	}
    	System.out.println();
    }
    static void print(long A[]) {
    	for(long i : A) {
    		System.out.print(i+" ");
    	}
    	System.out.println();
    }
	static void solve() {
		int t = sc.nextInt();
		while (t-- > 0) {
		   int n=sc.nextInt();
		   long c=sc.nextLong();
		   long k=sc.nextLong();
		   long arr[]=nextLongArray(n);
		   long ans=0,taken=0,count=1;
		   int arrSize = n;
		   for (int startPoint = 0; startPoint <arrSize ; startPoint++) {
            for (int grps = startPoint; grps <=arrSize ; grps++) {
                long sum=0;
                for (int j = startPoint ; j < grps ; j++) {
                    sum+=arr[j];      
                }
                if(sum>=k && sum<=c){
                    ans=Math.max(ans,grps-startPoint);
                }
            }
        }
        System.out.println(ans);
		}
	}
}

// Problem: ARRQUERY 
//Queries in Array
import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;
class Solution {
	static Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
	public static void reverse(int[] arr, int l, int r) {
		int d = (r - l + 1) / 2;
		for (int i = 0; i < d; i++) {
			int t = arr[l + i];
			arr[l + i] = arr[r - i];
			arr[r - i] = t;
		}
	}
	// QUICK MATHS
    private static int gcd(int a, int b) {
        if (b == 0)
            return a;
        return gcd(b, a % b);
    }

    private static long gcd(long a, long b) {
        if (b == 0)
            return a;
        return gcd(b, a % b);
    }

    private static int lcm(int a, int b) {
        return (a / gcd(a, b)) * b;
    }

    private static long lcm(long a, long b) {
        return (a / gcd(a, b)) * b;
    }
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		solve();
	}
	// BIT MAGIC
    public int getMSB(int b) {
        return (int)(Math.log(b) / Math.log(2));
    }
    //HELPER FUNCTIONS
    private static int[] nextArray(int n){
        int arr[]=new int[n];
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            arr[i]=sc.nextInt();
        }
        return arr;
    }
    private static long[] nextLongArray(int n){
        long arr[]=new long[n];
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            arr[i]=sc.nextLong();
        }
        return arr;
    }
    static int[] copy(int A[]) {
        int B[]=new int[A.length];
        for(int i=0;i<A.length;i++) {
            B[i]=A[i];
        }
        return B;
    }
    static long[] copy(long A[]) {
        long B[]=new long[A.length];
        for(int i=0;i<A.length;i++) {
            B[i]=A[i];
        }
        return B;
    }
    static long sum(int A[]) {
    	long sum=0;
    	for(int i : A) {
    		sum+=i;
    	}
    	return sum;
    }
    static long sum(long A[]) {
    	long sum=0;
    	for(long i : A) {
    		sum+=i;
    	}
    	return sum;
    }
    static void print(int A[]) {
    	for(int i : A) {
    		System.out.print(i+" ");
    	}
    	System.out.println();
    }
    static void print(long A[]) {
    	for(long i : A) {
    		System.out.print(i+" ");
    	}
    	System.out.println();
    }
	static void solve() {
        int n=sc.nextInt();
		int q = sc.nextInt();
		int a[] = new int[n];
		for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
		{
		    a[i]=sc.nextInt();
		}
		for(int j=0;j<q;j++)
		{
		    int l =sc.nextInt();
		    int r=sc.nextInt();
		    int x =sc.nextInt();
		    int cnt=-1;
		    for(int k=l-1;k<r;k++)
		    {
		        if(a[k]>=x)
		        {
		            cnt=k;
		            break;
		        }
		    }
		    if(cnt==-1)
		    {
		        System.out.println(0);
		    }
		    else
		    {
		        System.out.println(r-cnt);
		    }
		}
	}
}

// Problem: LVECHF 
//Love and Chef 
import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;
class Solution {
	static Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
	public static void reverse(int[] arr, int l, int r) {
		int d = (r - l + 1) / 2;
		for (int i = 0; i < d; i++) {
			int t = arr[l + i];
			arr[l + i] = arr[r - i];
			arr[r - i] = t;
		}
	}
	// QUICK MATHS
    private static int gcd(int a, int b) {
        if (b == 0)
            return a;
        return gcd(b, a % b);
    }

    private static long gcd(long a, long b) {
        if (b == 0)
            return a;
        return gcd(b, a % b);
    }

    private static int lcm(int a, int b) {
        return (a / gcd(a, b)) * b;
    }

    private static long lcm(long a, long b) {
        return (a / gcd(a, b)) * b;
    }
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		solve();
	}
	// BIT MAGIC
    public int getMSB(int b) {
        return (int)(Math.log(b) / Math.log(2));
    }
    //HELPER FUNCTIONS
    private static int[] nextArray(int n){
        int arr[]=new int[n];
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            arr[i]=sc.nextInt();
        }
        return arr;
    }
    private static long[] nextLongArray(int n){
        long arr[]=new long[n];
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            arr[i]=sc.nextLong();
        }
        return arr;
    }
    static int[] copy(int A[]) {
        int B[]=new int[A.length];
        for(int i=0;i<A.length;i++) {
            B[i]=A[i];
        }
        return B;
    }
    static long[] copy(long A[]) {
        long B[]=new long[A.length];
        for(int i=0;i<A.length;i++) {
            B[i]=A[i];
        }
        return B;
    }
    static long sum(int A[]) {
    	long sum=0;
    	for(int i : A) {
    		sum+=i;
    	}
    	return sum;
    }
    static long sum(long A[]) {
    	long sum=0;
    	for(long i : A) {
    		sum+=i;
    	}
    	return sum;
    }
    static void print(int A[]) {
    	for(int i : A) {
    		System.out.print(i+" ");
    	}
    	System.out.println();
    }
    static void print(long A[]) {
    	for(long i : A) {
    		System.out.print(i+" ");
    	}
    	System.out.println();
    }
	static void solve() {
		int t = sc.nextInt();
		while (t-- > 0) {
		   int n=sc.nextInt();
		   long k=sc.nextLong();
		   long min=Long.MAX_VALUE;
		   long max=Long.MIN_VALUE;
		   long arr[]=new long[n];
		   for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
		       arr[i]=sc.nextLong();
		       max=Math.max(max,arr[i]);
		       min=Math.min(min,arr[i]);
		   }
        long ans=max;
		   while(min<=max){
		       long mid=min+(max-min)/2;
		       if(blackBox(arr,mid,k)){
		           ans=mid;
		           max=mid-1;
		       }else{
		           min=mid+1;
		       }
		   }
		   System.out.println(ans);
		}
	} 
	static boolean blackBox(long arr[],long mid,long k){
            long cary=0;
            for(long num:arr){
                if(cary>k || cary>mid) return false;
                long remaining_work=mid-cary;
                cary=Math.max((num-remaining_work),0);
            }
            return cary==0;
	}
}

06/05/2022, 13:45 - Ritesh Gondian Snake: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
#define ll long long int
#define endl "\n"
#define rep(i,a,b)        for(int i=a;i<b;i++)
#define in(a)             for(ll &i:a) cin>>i
#define out(v)            for(auto it: v) cout<<it<<" "; cout<<"\n"
#define all(x)            (x).begin(),(x).end()
#define sz(x)             ((int)(x).size())
using namespace std;
char changeDirection(char c){
   if(c=='N') return 'S';
   if(c=='S') return 'N';
   if(c=='W') return 'E';
   return 'W';
}
int intersection[100001]={0};
void solve(){

   int n,ans=0;
   cin>>n;

   map<int,map<char,string>> m;

   int start,end;
   string street;
   char direction;

   for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
      cin>>start>>end>>street>>direction;

         m[start][direction]=street;

         char opposite = changeDirection(direction);

         if(m[start][opposite]==street){
            if(intersection[start]==0) intersection[start]=1;
            else intersection[start]=2;
         }

         m[end][opposite]=street;
         if(m[end][direction]==street){
            if(intersection[end]==0) intersection[end]=1;
            else intersection[end]=2;
         }

   }   
   for(int i=0;i<100001;i++){
      if(intersection[i]==2) ans++;
   }
   cout<<ans<<endl;

}
int main() {
   ios_base::sync_with_stdio(0);
   cin.tie(0);
   cout.tie(0);
 //clock_t z = clock();
   int t = 1;
 //cin >> t;
   while(t--) solve();
//cout << "Run Time : " << ((double)(clock() - z) / CLOCKS_PER_SEC);
   return 0;
}

using namespace std;

class vector<int> NGE(vector<int> v)
{ vector<int> nge(v.size());
 stack<int> st; 
 for (int i = 0; i < v.size(); i++)
 {
     while ((!st.empty()) && (v[i] > v[st.top()])) 
     { 
         nge[st.top()] = i; st.pop();
         } 
         st.push(i);
         } 
         while (!st.empty())
         { 
             nge[st.top()] = -1; st.pop(); 
             
         } 
         return nge; 
    
}

int main() 
{ 
    int n, i;
    cin >> n;
    vector<int> vect;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    { int x; cin >> x; 
    vect.push_back(x); 
        
    } 
    vector<int> nge = NGE(vect);
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) 
    cout << ((nge[i] == (-1)) ? -1 : vect[nge[i]]) << " ";
    }

30/09/2022, 16:25 - Shailesh: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/7-main-components-of-a-website/
30/09/2022, 16:25 - Shailesh: Q4
30/09/2022, 16:28 - Ritesh Gondian Snake: Ans 5: 

There are the following three types of cloud service models -

Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)
Platform as a Service (PaaS)
Software as a Service (SaaS)


1.Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)

IaaS is also known as Hardware as a Service (HaaS). It is a computing infrastructure managed over the internet. The main advantage of using IaaS is that it helps users to avoid the cost and complexity of purchasing and managing the physical servers.



Characteristics of IaaS

There are the following characteristics of IaaS -

Resources are available as a service
Services are highly scalable
Dynamic and flexible
GUI and API-based access
Automated administrative tasks


Example: DigitalOcean, Linode, Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, Google Compute Engine (GCE), Rackspace, and Cisco Metacloud.

2.Platform as a Service (PaaS)

PaaS cloud computing platform is created for the programmer to develop, test, run, and manage the applications.



Characteristics of PaaS

There are the following characteristics of PaaS -

Accessible to various users via the same development application.
Integrates with web services and databases.
Builds on virtualization technology, so resources can easily be scaled up or down as per the organization's need.
Support multiple languages and frameworks.
Provides an ability to "Auto-scale".


Example: AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Windows Azure, Heroku, Force.com, Google App Engine, Apache Stratos, Magento Commerce Cloud, and OpenShift.

3.Software as a Service (SaaS)

SaaS is also known as "on-demand software". It is a software in which the applications are hosted by a cloud service provider. Users can access these applications with the help of internet connection and web browser.



Characteristics of SaaS

There are the following characteristics of SaaS -



Managed from a central location

Hosted on a remote server

Accessible over the internet

Users are not responsible for hardware and software updates. Updates are applied automatically.

The services are purchased on the pay-as-per-use basis

Example: BigCommerce, Google Apps, Salesforce, Dropbox, ZenDesk, Cisco WebEx, ZenDesk, Slack, and GoToMeeting.

28/11/2022, 20:42 - Mavi Akela Khayega Kela: Dear Sir / Madam,

 

CAT 3 Assessment for Fall 2022-23 Higher Semester shall be conducted from 01.12.2022 to 05.12.2022 by the concerned course faculty during their scheduled class hours. The faculty can collect the CAT3 reports/case studies, etc. through LMS only.

 

All should follow the GU guidelines for CAT3 assessment as per the attached file. The summary sheet for CAT 3 topics given to the students and rubrics followed for evaluation are to be prepared and documented in the LMS/course file.

 

Note:

As per the instruction of higher authorities conducting of exam through PPT /Presentation is strictly not allowed. So, all are instructed to prepared the questions in the proper format, upload in the LMS and conduct the exam. After students upload proper evaluation should be done by the faculty in the LMS only. 



Guidelines for CAT-3

1.       CAT-3 will be conducted at School level, Coordinated by Dean / School Exam Coordinator

2.       CAT 3 will be activity based, targeted towards Creativity, Innovation and Critical Thinking

3.       The Complete assessment will be activity based on CO -5 and CO-6

4.       Faculty can decide the activity and Rubrics, in line with the guidelines given below, in consultation with the Course Coordinator, Division Chair and get it approved by PC / Dean.

5.       Common Courses must share the Same Rubric and assessment pattern

6.       Maximum Mark will be 30

7.       Time duration can be fixed based on activity

8.       Group activities can also be given, with Maximum 3 students in a group and Same Problem / Case Study can be given to 3  Groups

9.       Solutions for the Problems must be unique and report must be minimum of 6 pages and maximum up-to 10 Pages, including Diagrams, Algorithm, Interpretation of Results, Review of Literature etc

10.   The Report (PDF, Docx) must be screened through itenticate and plagiarism must be less than 10%

11.   Few suggestions for CAT-3 activities are (Recommended but not limited to)

o   Open ended Problems

o   Case Study

o   Simulations

o   Research papers

o   Lab work

o   Reflections

o   Problem-based activities

o   Role Play

o   Report / essay / Blog

o   Field experience/report

o   Group assignments

o   Any other relevant tools as appropriate, and approved by School Dean

05/12/2022, 10:43 - Shailesh: #include<iostream>
#include<cmath>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    string n1 = "99";
    string n2 = "999";

    int r = 0;
    int size;
    int size_diff;
    if(n1.size() > n2.size())
    {
        size = n2.size();
        size_diff = n1.size() - n2.size();
        while(size_diff--)
        {
            n2 = '0' + n2;
        }
    }
    else
    {
        size = n1.size();
        size_diff = n2.size() - n1.size();
        while(size_diff--)
        {
            n1 = '0' + n1;
        }
    }

    int n1_size = n1.size();
    int n2_size = n2.size();

    string new_string = "";
    for(int i = n1.size()-1; i >= 0; i--)
    {
        int digit_sum=n1[n1_size-1] + n2[n2_size-1] - 96 + r;
        r = 0;

        if(digit_sum > 9)
        {
            r = digit_sum/10;
            digit_sum = digit_sum - 10;
        }

        char num_digit = digit_sum + 48;
        new_string = num_digit + new_string;
        // cout << num_digit << " " << r << " ";
        n1_size--;
        n2_size--;
    }
    if(r > 0)
    {
        new_string = (char)(r+48) + new_string;
    }
    cout << new_string;
    return 0;
}
05/12/2022, 10:43 - Shailesh: String Sum
05/12/2022, 11:03 - Shailesh: // A Naive Java recursive implementation
// of LCS of two strings

class GFG {

// Returns length of LCS for X[0..m-1], Y[0..n-1]
	static int lcs(String X, String Y, int m, int n) {
		if (m == 0 || n == 0) {
			return 0;
		}

		if (X.charAt(m - 1) == Y.charAt(n - 1)) {
			return 1 + lcs(X, Y, m - 1, n - 1);
		} else {
			return Math.max(lcs(X, Y, m, n - 1),
					lcs(X, Y, m - 1, n));
		}
	}
// Driver Code

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		String X = "AGGTAB";
		String Y = "GXTXAYB";

		// Find the length of String
		int m = X.length();
		int n = Y.length();
		System.out.println("Length of LCS: " + lcs(X, Y, m, n));

	}
}

// This code is contributed by 29AjayKumar
05/12/2022, 11:03 - Shailesh: LCS
05/12/2022, 11:03 - Shailesh: Java
05/12/2022, 11:03 - Shailesh: # A Naive recursive Python implementation of LCS problem

def lcs(X, Y, m, n):

	if m == 0 or n == 0:
		return 0
	elif X[m-1] == Y[n-1]:
		return 1 + lcs(X, Y, m-1, n-1);
	else:
		return max(lcs(X, Y, m, n-1), lcs(X, Y, m-1, n));


# Driver program to test the above function
X = "AGGTAB"
Y = "GXTXAYB"
print ("Length of LCS is ", lcs(X , Y, len(X), len(Y)) )

16/05/2023, 12:40 - Shailesh: Extract Email Addresses: UiPath


User
Automate a process that extract the email address from a string in ui path

ChatGPT
Sure! I can guide you on how to automate a process to extract email addresses from a string using UiPath. Here's a step-by-step guide:

Step 1: Create a new UiPath project
Open UiPath Studio and create a new project. Give it a suitable name and select the location to save the project.

Step 2: Design the workflow
In the Designer panel, drag and drop an Input Dialog activity to prompt the user to enter the string containing email addresses. Add a variable to store the input.

Next, add a Matches activity from the Toolbox. Set the Input property to the variable containing the string. In the Pattern field, enter the regular expression pattern to match email addresses. You can use the following pattern as a starting point: \b[A-Za-z0-9._%+-]+@[A-Za-z0-9.-]+\.[A-Za-z]{2,}\b.

Add a For Each activity and set the TypeArgument to System.Text.RegularExpressions.Match. Set the Values property to MatchesOutput (the output variable from the Matches activity).

Inside the For Each loop, add an Assign activity to extract the email address. Create a new variable, let's say emailAddress, and set its value to item.Value.

Step 3: Display or store the extracted email addresses
Depending on your requirements, you can choose to display the email addresses or store them for further processing. For displaying, you can use a Message Box activity inside the For Each loop and pass the emailAddress variable as the message.

If you want to store the email addresses, create a List variable, e.g., emailList, before the For Each loop. Inside the loop, use an Add To Collection activity to add each emailAddress to the emailList variable.

Step 4: Run the automation
Save the project and run the automation. It will prompt you to enter the string containing email addresses. After providing the input, UiPath will extract the email addresses and either display them or store them in a list.

Remember to test the automation with different scenarios to ensure it handles various email address formats correctly.

16/05/2023, 13:34 - Ritesh Gondian Snake: UiPath RE Framework Activity


User
What is RE Framework? Create an activity with the help of RE Framework. Also, explain the 
step-by-step procedure of the activity in UI path 

ChatGPT
The RE Framework (Robotic Enterprise Framework) is a template or framework provided by UiPath that helps in building scalable and robust automation solutions. It follows a standardized approach to automate business processes, providing features such as exception handling, logging, and transaction recovery. The RE Framework is based on the principles of the State Machine design pattern and is widely used in UiPath for developing enterprise-level automation projects.

To create an activity using the RE Framework in UiPath, you can follow these step-by-step procedures:

Step 1: Create a New Project

Open UiPath Studio and click on "Blank" under the "New Project" section.
Provide a name for your project and choose a location to save it.
Click on "Create" to create the new project.
Step 2: Add the RE Framework Template

In the Project panel, right-click on the "Main" file under the "Workflows" folder.
Select "Add" and then click on "ReFramework" from the sub-menu.
The RE Framework template will be added to your project.
Step 3: Customize the Framework

Open the "InitAllApplications.xaml" file under the "Framework" folder.
Modify this workflow to initialize the applications and systems required for your specific automation process.
Add activities to interact with the application interfaces, perform login operations, or set up any necessary configurations.
Step 4: Implement the Process Workflow

Open the "Process.xaml" file under the "Framework" folder.
This is where you'll build the main workflow for your automation process.
Use the provided states (Init, GetTransactionData, ProcessTransaction, EndProcess) to define the flow of your automation.
Implement activities within each state to perform specific actions related to your process, such as data scraping, data manipulation, or data entry.
Step 5: Configure Config and Transaction Data

Open the "Config.xlsx" file under the "Data" folder.
Customize the configuration settings according to your automation requirements. This includes adding asset names, application URLs, or other parameters.
Add transaction data in the "TransactionData" sheet. Each row represents a single transaction item for processing.
Step 6: Handle Exceptions and Logging

The RE Framework provides built-in exception handling and logging mechanisms.
Open the "Main.xaml" file under the "Workflows" folder.
Customize the exception handling and logging activities within the "Process Transaction" state to meet your specific needs.
Add activities to capture and handle exceptions, log messages, or send notifications.
Step 7: Run the Automation

Save your project and click on the "Start" button in UiPath Studio to run the automation.
The RE Framework will execute the defined workflow, processing each transaction item and handling exceptions and logging as per the configured settings.
Monitor the output and logs to verify the success and progress of your automation.

what is CRED?

 

CRED is an exclusive community for Indiaâ€™s most trustworthy and creditworthy individuals, where the members are rewarded for good financial behavior. CRED was born out of a need to bring back the focus on a long lost virtue, one of trust, the idea being to create a community centered around this virtue. a community that constantly strives to become more virtuous in this regard till they finally scale their behavior to create a utopia where being trustworthy is the norm and not the exception. to build a community like this requires a community of its own; a community special in its own way, working towards making this vision come true. 

 

hereâ€™s a thought experiment: what do you get when you put a group of incredibly passionate and driven people and entrust them with the complete freedom to chase down their goals in a completely uninhibited manner? answer: you get something close to what we have at CRED; CRED just has it better.

 

hereâ€™s what will be in store for you at CRED once you join as a part of the team 

 

what you will do?

Â· work on a disruptive product thatâ€™s still in its early stages

Â· be responsible to drive innovation in software development, while relentlessly improving performance, scalability, and maintainability.

Â· owning the design process, implementation, and verification of framework components leveraging standard software engineering methodologies

Â· translating functional and technical requirements into detailed architecture and design.

you should apply if you:

Â· have good exposure in front end ui frameworks like reactjs, svelte, or similar.

Â· have a thorough knowledge of html, css and javascript.

Â· have very good analytical and problem solving skills.

Â· have Willingness to constantly learn and if you are looking for ways to improve yourself and the processes around you.

Â· have experience working in agile team environments and are a self-starter, conscientious member of the team.

Â· have passion to code, but also youâ€™re awesome at it!

how is life at CRED?

 

working at CRED would instantly make you realize one thing: you are working with the best talent around you. not just in the role you occupy, but everywhere you go. talk to someone around you; most likely you will be talking to a singer, standup comic, artist, writer, an athlete, maybe a magician.

 

at CRED people always have talent up their sleeves. with the right company, even conversations can be rejuvenating. at CRED, we guarantee a good company.

 

hard truths: pushing oneself comes with the role. and we realise pushing oneself is hard work. which is why CRED is in the continuous process of building an environment that helps the team rejuvenate oneself: included but not limited to a stacked, in-house pantry, with lunch and dinner provided for all the team members, paid sick leaves and a comprehensive health insurance. 

 

to make things smoother and to make sure you spend time and energy only on the most important things,  CRED strives to make every process transparent: there are no work timings because we do not believe in archaic methods of calculating productivity, your work should speak for you. there are no job designations because you will be expected to hold down roles that cannot be described in one word. since trust is a major virtue in the community we have built, we make it a point to highlight it in the community behind CRED: all our employees get their salaries before their joining date. a show of trust that speaks volumes because of the skin in the game. 

 

there are many more such eccentricities that make CRED what it is but thatâ€™s for one to discover.

if you feel at home reading this, get in touch.

17/09/2023, 15:59 - UP -65 Dalaal: class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> combinationSum(vector<int>& A, int N, int B) {
        vector<vector<int>> result;
        vector<int> current;
        
        // Sort the input array to ensure non-decreasing order
        sort(A.begin(), A.end());
        
        backtrack(A, B, 0, current, result);
        
        return result;
    }

private:
    void backtrack(vector<int>& A, int target, int start, vector<int>& current, vector<vector<int>>& result) {
        if (target == 0) {
            result.push_back(current);
            return;
        }
        
        for (int i = start; i < A.size(); i++) {
            // Skip duplicates to avoid duplicate combinations
            if (i > start && A[i] == A[i - 1]) {
                continue;
            }
            
            // Ensure non-decreasing order
            if (A[i] <= target) {
                current.push_back(A[i]);
                backtrack(A, target - A[i], i + 1, current, result);
                current.pop_back();
            }
        }
    }
};
